Upcoming Events

 

 










An Invitation to industry What it means for products




 Fast cure speeds at ambient temperatures significantly reducing cycle times, increasing throughput, reducing energy costs, and enabling new material selections in a broad range of customer and consumer applications, automotive, electronics, millwork, packaging, and hygiene. 






Drastically Reduce
Cure Time

Cure time, from automotive component bonding, to protective and maintenance coating, to can coatings, poses the key bottleneck to expedited access to these respective markets. This feature translates to lower applied costs via a combination of lower labor costs, increased overall throughput, reduced asset downtimes, no heat or ultraviolet light associated with the cure of many other adhesives and coatings, and in many cases, lower rework rates. Combined, these benefits reduce applied costs of fifty percent or more in many applications.









Reduction of Thermal Energy Input

Tied with expedited cure time, applications such as vehicle paint, injection molding, and wind blade manufacturing currently require thermal heating to cure. Our Chemilian monomer platform cures at ambient temperatures, and diminishes the need for thermal heat curing, a process that requires an extraordinary amount of energy and significant capital costs. These benefits are particularly salient for new construction and regions where energy delivery is expensive or challenging.










Elimination of
Hazardous Materials

BPA in can coatings, formaldehyde in wood composites, and styrene in glass fibers pose insidious threats to human health. Regulatory limits have been imposed, especially on BPA usage in children’s products. The Sirrus-developed monomer platform offers viable substitutes for these harmful chemicals, many of which currently lack performance-driven solutions.









Performance Improvement

Our class of monomers have physical properties that allow the resulting polymer to be exposed to tough environmental conditions, including high heat, high humidity, solvents and other environmental exposure. Additionally, due to the unique cure system that our products enable, we allow for a change in partner business model and substrate selection. Potential results include lower cost manufacturing, enhanced just in time manufacturing, and discrete assembly.














The chemical reaction Anionic Polymerization
This reaction occurs in our materials rapidly at room temperature, allowing partners to make high molecular weight reactive products, such as, coatings, adhesives, inks, resins and sealants. 
















"As a step-change in technology, Chemilian and Forza invite industrial customers of all types to think about their assembly and manufacturing processes in new ways."
- Jeff Sullivan, Ph.D., Senior VP R&D 















Meet ChemilianTM & ForzaTM Introducing a breakthrough





 
 
ChemilianTM
ChemilianTM products have one alkene group with the potential to have a wide variety of substituent terminal or functional groups, that can be used to make high molecular weight polymers.





 
 


 
 
ForzaTM
ForzaTM products contain multiple alkene groups allowing cross-linking for the development of polymers exhibiting high strength, thermal and chemical resistance.














Brought to you by Sirrus A step-change in technology










 
Sirrus has developed a new chemical platform based on 1,1-disubstituted alkene monomers that will allow many current chemical processes to be done faster and/or with less energy.
 









 
The materials we are manufacturing will be used to make new components that can be formulated into plastics, rubber, films, coatings, inks, sealants, adhesives and other products.
 









 
The combination of multiple reactive sites that includes a fast curing alkene group allow for the creation of many new compounds having a unique combination of properties.
 














Our proprietary technology enables us to manufacture, stabilize, activate and formulate a new class of materials.





















About UsOur HeritageOur LeadershipBoard of DirectorsInvestorsCareers 
Sirrus advances manufacturing technology through chemistry relating to the synthesis, stabilization, activation and formulation of a unique and reactive class of monomers commonly known as methylene malonates. These monomers, their derivatives and resulting polymer platforms provide the foundation for enabling our customers to meet their customers needs through our game-changing technology.
Currently known for Chemilian™ and Forza™, Sirrus provides the next generation of adhesive, sealant, coating and resin solutions for various manufacturing and assembly industries. The Sirrus polymerization-on-demand technology currently provides fast cure speeds at ambient temperatures to significantly reduce cycle times, increase throughput, reduce energy costs, and enable new material selection in a broad range of customer and consumer applications, including auto, electronics, packaging and hygiene.



The Past, Present & Future
Bernie Malofsky accepts the 2013 AWFS VISIONARY AWARD from Angelo Gangone, the Executive VP of the AWFS, in July 2013, in Las Vegas, NV.
 
Sirrus, formerly known as Bioformix, was founded in 2009 by the father and son team of Bernie and Adam Malofsky. The Malofskys identified the initial chemical concepts which ultimately led to our premier monomer products, ChemilianTM and ForzaTM.
The commitment to science and technology, which drives Sirrus, stems from the philosophy of Bernie Malofsky whose resume includes:
 

A 25+ year career in the Loctite Corporation’s adhesives division
Leadership of Loctite’s New Business Development Program, where he managed over 100 research & development professionals, 60 service and development specialists and dozens of commercial development sales representatives
Worked with Harry Coover, the inventor of SuperGlue, to make the formula more useful in wider areas of applications
Authorship of dozens of patents in the U.S.

 
 
“Always stay persistent and passionate about whatever you choose to do.  When you run into obstacles – and you always will at some point – your persistence and passion will carry you through and you will overcome all of your challenges.”  — Bernie Malofsky






  



Jeff Uhrig
Chief Executive Officer
Jeff, whose background includes both corporate development and investment banking in the biobased materials sector comes to Sirrus from Elevance Renewable Sciences, where he led corporate development for the producer of high performance, renewable specialty chemicals and materials. At Elevance, Jeff was responsible for evaluating and implementing value-capture strategies, developing partnerships, evaluating technology and leading fundraising for the venture capital-backed company.
Prior to Elevance, Jeff worked in investment banking at Piper Jaffray as Vice President for its Clean Technology and Renewables Group. Among his responsibilities, he led transaction execution for a variety of deal types, built detailed valuation models for potential investments and managed relationships with leading clean technology companies and investors.
Jeff earned a B.S. in Chemical Engineering from the University of Illinois in Urbana, IL. He also holds an M.S. with distinction in Engineering Management and an M.B.A. from Northwestern University in Evanston, IL. 






  



Jeff Sullivan, Ph.D.
Senior Vice President, Research & Development
Jeff, a proven chemist and innovator, is tasked with building the company’s Research & Development organization, directing its chemical technology, and facilitating innovation and intellectual property creation. He and his team will play a leading role in fulfilling Sirrus’ mission of creating and commercializing new technologies.
Prior to joining Sirrus, Jeff was the Chief Technical Officer at Shepherd Chemical Company where he developed and executed the company’s global technology goals. Additionally, he designed and built several of the company’s state-of-the-art laboratories and an advanced materials pilot facility. Jeff has co-authored numerous scientific articles and also holds 25+ patents including one for methylene malonates and the synthesis, processing and preparation of various chemical compounds.
Jeff earned a Ph.D. in chemistry, M.S. in Analytical Chemistry from Colorado State University in Fort Collins, Colorado and conducted his post-doctoral fellowship at the University of Alberta in Edmonton, Alberta. He also earned a B.A. in Classics and Mathematics at Washington & Lee University in Lexington, Va. 






 

Robert Pangborn, Ph.D.
Executive Chairman
Bob, an internationally recognized polymer and green chemistry expert, provides business strategy expertise.
Bob, the founder of Pangborn Associates, LLC, advises pre-IPO companies in the chemical, materials, and energy industries. Past and current clients include Diversa, Materia, CSP Technologies, Metabolix and Genomatica. Bob also served as a senior advisor to Cargill’s Industrial BioProducts Division, and played a key role in helping develop and implement strategy for this key corporate growth initiative. Previously, Bob was employed at Dow Chemical in a variety of R&D and business leadership roles, rising to the post of Vice President of Central Research and Development.
Bob holds a Ph.D. in Physics from Dartmouth, attended Harvard Business School, and was an officer in the United States Marine Corps.


Doug Cameron, Ph.D.
Director
Doug is world renowned as a Cleantech and Green Chemistry industry expert and is the co-founder of venture capital firm, First Green Partners. He is a prominent scientist, businessman and thought-leader in the areas of clean technology and sustainable agriculture. Doug’s career has spanned business, finance and academia, including positions at Khosla Ventures, Piper Jaffray, Cargill, and the University of Wisconsin, Madison. In 2009, Doug received the prestigious Raphael Katzen Award for his contributions in furthering the deployment and commercialization of biotechnology to produce fuels and chemicals from renewable resources. Doug continues to serve on the Scientific Advisory Boards of Mascoma and Segetis. While at Cargill, he built and led the corporate biotechnology research group, and also spearheaded the company’s biotech activities in China.
Doug graduated magna cum laude from Duke University with a B.S. in Engineering in Biomedical Engineering and earned a Ph.D. in Biochemical Engineering from the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.​


Kieran Drain, Ph.D.
Director
Kieran is a broadly experienced C-level chemical executive.
Kieran, currently CEO of the Tyndall National Institute in Ireland, one of Europe’s premier ICT research institutes, has been most recently Vice President & General Manager at Rambus, Inc., and prior to that, President & CEO of Silicon Valley Technology company, NanoGram Corporation. Prior to joining NanoGram Corporation, he was Vice President and General Manager for the Performance Polymers Division of Avery Dennison Corporation with prior leadership roles at Ciba Specialty Chemicals and Loctite Corporation (now Henkel). Kieran has more than thirty years industrial experience in technology and business management in diverse industrial segments including solid state lighting, photovoltaics, rechargeable batteries, LCD displays, electronics interconnect, automotive, and composites.
Kieran holds a Ph.D. in Industrial Chemistry, a MSc in Polymer Chemistry and a BSc in Pharmacy degrees from The Queens University of Belfast in Northern Ireland, an MBA (Finance and Accounting) from Regis University in Denver, Colorado and is a Fellow of the Royal Society of Chemistry, United Kingdom.


John Habbert
Director
John’s deep start-up experience provides tactical and investment know-how.
A near 20-year veteran of entrepreneurship, John is one of the founders and leaders of Queen City Angels (QCA), one of the oldest, most successful and well respected angel investment groups in the United States. John has been a member of QCA since its founding in 2001 and has been involved in virtually all of its investments. Prior to that, John was a consultant and interim President of Antiqnet, which through subsequent mergers became GoAntiques.com. John was the President of Crane Connectors, a manufacturer of electronic connectors. In his early career, John worked in a variety of leadership and operational roles at Procter & Gamble.
John holds a B.S. in Chemical Engineering from Case Western Reserve as well as an M.B.A. from the University of Michigan.


William D. Lese
Director
Bill’s 27 years of energy investment experience drives Sirrus’s business strategy.
Prior to co-founding Braemar, Bill was a partner with Mantis Holdings, Inc., a venture capital firm focused on investing in environmental and energy-efficiency companies, where he concentrated on emerging technologies for converting industrial waste streams into value-added products. Prior to Mantis Holdings, he was the director of business development for NPS Industries, Inc., an international manufacturer of engineered equipment for the power industry. Bill’s business development activities included managing a joint venture with Consolidated Edison Co., and managing other key customer relationships. Prior to joining NPS Industries, he was one of the original employees of Sithe Energies, Inc. (an affiliate of Vivendi, SA), which became one of the world’s largest independent power producers. At Sithe Energies, Bill had project and technical oversight responsibilities, including managing several power projects.
Bill has both a B.A. in Physics and an M.S. in Energy Science from New York University.


Adam Malofsky, Ph.D.
Director, Co-Founder
Adam is a 25-year veteran of the chemicals, polymers and performance materials industries.
Adam has held numerous leadership positions in a variety of chemical industry start-up opportunities, both private and within corporate America. Adam is known for identifying white space opportunities and then developing and employing practical, high speed, value oriented development strategies that frequently allow for the successful commercialization of new technology platforms, not simply evolutionary improvements. Adam has extensive experience in managing start-up efforts in product materials, processing and assembly with far ranging experience in industries from aerospace adhesives to shelf life products for fresh cut produce.
Adam received a B.S. in Chemical Engineering from Lehigh, an M.S. in Polymer Science and a Ph.D. in Polymer Science from the University of Connecticut.


John Trbovich
Director
John’s deep defense industry experience guides emerging company growth.
John is a Managing Director of Arsenal Venture Partnerships. He was previously a principal investor in the communications and information technology sectors, and a co-founder and principal of E*OFFERING. Prior to E*OFFERING, John was a senior technology banker at Robertson Stephens & Co., where he participated in raising billions of dollars for technology companies as well as advising on mergers and acquisitions. Previously, John worked in merchant banking for Metzler Corp., the oldest privately held German bank, and the investment banking department of Salomon Smith Barney.
John is a graduate of the Harvard Business School and the School of Engineering at Columbia University.


Jeff Uhrig
Director
Jeff’s broad experience in corporate development and investment banking drives his leadership of Sirrus.
Jeff, whose background includes both corporate development and investment banking in the biobased materials sector comes to Sirrus from Elevance Renewable Services, where he led corporate development for the producer of high performance, renewable specialty chemicals and materials. At Elevance, Jeff was responsible for evaluating and implementing value-capture strategies, developing partnerships, evaluating technology and leading fundraising for the venture capital-backed company.
Prior to Elevance, Jeff worked in investment banking at Piper Jaffray as Vice President for its Clean Technology and Renewables Group. Among his responsibilities, he led transaction execution for a variety of deal types, built detailed valuation models for potential investments and managed relationships with leading clean technology companies and investors.
Jeff earned a B.S. in Chemical Engineering from the University of Illinois in Urbana, IL. He also holds an M.S. with distinction in Engineering Management and an M.B.A. from Northwestern University in Evanston, IL..







  

Braemar Energy Ventures
 Braemar Energy Ventures is a leading energy venture capital firm. Their principals have more than 100 years of combined energy experience, and an investment record that dates back to the mid-1980s. Braemar Energy Ventures partners with exceptional companies and management teams, in both alternative and traditional energy markets, that can contribute to a more profitable and efficient energy landscape through innovation and marketplace expertise. 





  

Arsenal Venture Partners
 Arsenal Venture Partners (AVP) is the leading venture capital firm focused on the intersection of the commercial and defense markets. AVP, formerly known as MILCOM Venture Partners, manages multiple early-stage venture capital funds including Arsenal Venture Partners II, OnPoint Technologies, and MILCOM Technologies. 





  

The Queen City Angels
 The Queen City Angels (QCA) is the first group of experienced, accredited investors committed to accelerating the growth of outstanding early-stage businesses in the Cincinnati area and the surrounding region, via smart investments capable of producing a substantial return. 






  

CincyTech
 CincyTech is a publicly backed seed stage venture development company that invests in technology-based companies in southwest Ohio. 






Sirrus is a diverse and eclectic group of people who love what they do, and we are always looking for smart and engaged professionals who embrace challenges to join our team.
Whether working to create new technologies in the lab or managing a balance sheet, our team members work in an exciting environment where they have the opportunity to contribute to the development of truly game-changing chemistry.
We offer competitive salaries, enhanced benefits, including health, dental and professional development opportunities and a mature vacation policy.
